\par\par \b \uc2 CGI may provide $2.7b in new loans for Indonesia   \b0\par\par\uc2 The Jakarta Post, Jakarta   \par \uc2 568 \uc2 words\par \uc2 9 December 2003\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 3\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2003 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 The country may obtain some US$2.7 billion in fresh loans from the Consultative Group on Indonesia (CGI) to help finance next year's state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The amount is the same as that pledged last year by the donor grouping for the current 2003 \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 World Bank lead economist Bert Hofman said on Monday the amount would be within the range $2.3 billion to $3 billion, which the government planned to request when the CGI held its two-day annual meeting on Dec. 10.   \par \par \uc2 "We may come out with the same amount as last year (for the 2003 \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 )," Hofman told a news briefing when launching the bank's brief report to the CGI. The bank will chair the upcoming meeting of the country's traditional donor grouping.   \par \par \uc2 In the report, it was said that next year would pose an uphill financial challenge for Indonesia in view of the absence of a special program from the International Monetary Fund (IMF), which deprives the country of the debt relief facility from the Paris Club of creditor nations.   \par \par \uc2 The situation leaves Indonesia little choice but to remain dependent on its usual foreign donors.   \par \par \uc2 "Financing needs will increase in 2004 despite further \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  consolidation, as exceptional financing dries up with the end of the IMF program, and debt service will increase from 31 percent of revenue in 2003 to 37 percent in 2004," said the report.   \par \par \uc2 The impact from the absence of the Paris Club debt rescheduling facility alone means that the amortization of \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  debt next year is expected to rise by $2.6 billion.   \par \par \uc2 Under the 2004 state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the government is setting its sights on proceeds from bond sales, both domestic and international; privatization; the sale of banks and assets under the Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency; bank financing and loans from foreign lenders -- mostly the CGI.   \par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  has targeted a state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  of Rp 24.4 trillion, or some 1.2 percent of the country's gross domestic product (GDP), as compared with the estimated Rp 34.4 trillion (1.8 percent GDP) \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  for this year.   \par \par \uc2 The CGI has been a crucial financing source to which the country turns to help it plug the annual state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 International donors are hoping the next loans will provide an incentive for the country to remain committed to reform.   \par \par \uc2 The bank said that while praising efforts to restore macroeconomic stability amid various internal and external shocks, attempts to improve the investment climate to boost growth and reduce poverty lagged behind.   \par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  -- while expected to grow by about 4 percent this year amid shocks resulting from the Iraq war, the SARS epidemic and a bomb attack on a Jakarta hotel -- remains driven largely by consumption amid weak investment and export performance.   \par \par \uc2 Strong and sustainable \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth should be supported by healthy investment growth.   \par \par \uc2 Foreign direct investment (FDI) approvals in the first ten months of the year stood at $9.3 billion, rising from the same period of last year but still only a quarter of the precrisis level, the World Bank report said.   \par \par \uc2 The Bank cited a survey among 1,000 domestic and foreign companies that highlighted microeconomic instability, \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  as well as corruption, as areas that investors thought needed plenty of improvement to strengthen the investment climate.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020031208dzc90000b\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
