ed an option for Cemex to increase its stake to 51 percent by the end of 2001. Cemex is the world's third largest cement maker.   \par \par \uc2 However, the government could not perform its side of the deal due to strong protests from PT Semen Padang, the West Sumatra-based unit of Semen Gresik, and local politicians, who ostensibly claimed to be opposed to the idea of the company being controlled by a foreign investor. Attempts to resolve this problem have been unsuccessful, leaving Cemex's investment here facing an \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  future.   \par \par \uc2 Cemex has asked the ICSID to rescind the 1998 purchase agreement and demanded the government of Indonesia cover the company's investment outlay and pay damages.   \par \par \uc2 But a spokesman for Cemex in Jakarta last week told The Jakarta Post that an out of court settlement was still possible as long as the government could come up with a "convincing proposal".   \par \par \uc2 Laksamana said that the government was now in negotiation with Cemex to seek the best possible solution to the case. Analysts have said the Cemex case could further undermine foreign investor confidence in the country.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020031215dzcg0000a\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
