\par\par \b \uc2 Corruption a serious threat to business sector, Kadin says  \b0\par\par\uc2 Fitri Wulandari, The Jakarta Post , Jakarta  \par \uc2 476 \uc2 words\par \uc2 23 December 2003\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 13\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2003 The Jakarta Post  \par \par \uc2 Rampant corruption, coupled with ineffective bureaucracy and unfavorable industrial relations, remains the main obstacle in doing business in this country, the Indonesian Chamber of Commerce and Industry (Kadin) said in its year-end assessment.  \par \par \uc2 Kadin chairman Aburizal Bakrie told a media conference on Monday that corruption and collusive business practices had created \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and worsened the investment climate here.  \par \par \uc2 Aburizal cited a study from the prestigious University of Indonesia that shows that businesses have to set aside 10 percent to 11 percent of production costs for bribes.  \par \par \uc2 He explained that one of the direct impacts of the above problems was a slowdown in the recovery of the country's crucial manufacturing sector, which has seen a decline in production capacity, as new investment in the sector remains low despite hard-won macroeconomic stability.  \par \par \uc2 The recovery of this sector is important as it can provide a huge number of jobs for the millions of people left jobless following the late-1990s \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis.  \par \par \uc2 Aburizal also criticized the country's ineffective bureaucracy.  \par \par \uc2 He cited a World Bank study, which shows that it takes 196 days to set up a company in Indonesia, while it only takes 50 in Vietnam and 5 in Singapore.  \par \par \uc2 He said that corruption and the ineffective bureaucracy had worsened the country's competitiveness.  \par \par \uc2 The World \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Forum recently ranked Indonesia 60th of 102 countries surveyed in terms of business competitiveness.  \par \par \uc2 Aburizal said it was urgent to reform the bureaucracy in the country to reduce corruption and collusive business practices.  \par \par \uc2 Kadin plans to work with different groups as part of the organization's drive to combat corruption. The organization signed an antibribery pact last week with Muhammadiyah Students Association (IMM), under which IMM will be involved in an antibribery campaign.  \par \par \uc2 "We shall sign an antibribery pact with different groups, including students. We want to inform the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  that bribery is damaging and needs to be eliminated," Aburizal told The Jakarta Post.  \par \par \uc2 Aburizal added the business sector needed a business-friendly government.  \par \par \uc2 "We need a strong leader who can ignore political parties and select capable people who understand business and the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," he said.  \par \par \uc2 Aburizal cited the government's minimum wage \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  as an example of what was undermining the country's business competitiveness. He said that minimum wages in Jakarta were higher than those in Hanoi and Shanghai.  \par \par \uc2 The upcoming election also raises concern on whether it can produce a government that is committed to \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development, Aburizal added.  \par \par \uc2 "They want a government that can tackle problems like the rising price of goods, unemployment and other matters," he remarked.  \par \par \uc2 He said that improving the investment climate at home was crucial to attracting new investment to the country to help the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  grow at a faster rate and create more jobs.  \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020031222dzcn00017\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
