\par\par \b \uc2 Indef, LIPI see moderate growth for next year   \b0\par\par\uc2 Fitri Wulandari, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta   \par \uc2 637 \uc2 words\par \uc2 24 December 2003\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 3\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2003 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 The country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth is projected to remain at a moderate level of around 4 percent next year as \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  during the seven-month voting and campaigning periods will cause investment to remain weak.   \par \par \uc2 The Institute for Development of Economics and Finance (Indef) predicted the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to grow by between 4.2 and 4.4 percent in 2004, which is lower than the government's projection of 4.8 percent.   \par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, the state-sponsored Indonesian Science Institute (LIPI) said that if the general election process was not smooth, the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would only grow by 4 percent, which is the same level estimated for this year.   \par \par \uc2 Indef economist Drajad Wibowo said in a press conference on Tuesday that domestic consumption would continue to be the main engine of next year's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, as investment and exports would remain weak.   \par \par \uc2 Indef predicts political parties could spend around Rp 15 trillion next year on campaigning and other activities. This large amount of money will eventually mean a boost in domestic consumption.   \par \par \uc2 He said that investment may only start to enter the country in the second half of next year, assuming that the election process goes well.   \par \par \uc2 "Indonesia (\b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 ) would grow by 3.9 percent if there is no investment coming in next year," Drajad said.   \par \par \uc2 He added that export would also remain weak as local businesses would tend to focus on trading goods in the domestic market instead producing goods for the export market as competition from China and Vietnam becomes tougher. This is despite the expected recovery in the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which should increase demands for export products.   \par \par \uc2 For the past couple of years, the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  has been mainly driven by domestic consumption due to the weak performance of the investment and export sectors. Investors have been generally reluctant to pour in fresh money into the country due to a host of problems at home such as corruption, poor infrastructure, lingering labor conflicts and lack of faith in the judiciary.   \par \par \uc2 During the first nine months of this year, capital formation (a measure of investment) was 25 percent lower than the level prior to the 1997 \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis.   \par \par \uc2 But LIPI's economist Wijaya Adi said that there was also a possibility for the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to grow by 5.4 percent next year particularly if the elections go very well.   \par \par \uc2 He said that under such a scenario, the current trend of increasing stability in macro-\b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  indicators would push households and businesses to become more optimistic about the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , thus triggering higher investment.   \par \par \uc2 On the external front, the expected recovery in the economies of developed nations (export destinations for many local products) will also bode well for exports.   \par \par \uc2 In the worst case scenario, if the election disappoints the people and there is social unrest, the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will slow way down, while inflation will increase and the rupiah will weaken.   \par \par \uc2 During the past year, the country's macroeconomic indicators have improved as evidenced by the low inflation, stronger rupiah against the U.S. dollar and declining \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 Both Indef and LIPI warned of the possible worsening unemployment problem next year, particularly if the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  grows too slow.   \par \par \uc2 LIPI predicted that full unemployment this year would be 10.3 million people, a 14 percent increase from last year's 9.1 million. Next year the number could grow to 10.75 million jobless.   \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  indicators for 2004   \par \par \uc2 Indef LIPI   \par \par \uc2 GDP(%) 4.2 - 4.4 4.8 - 5.4   \par \par \uc2 Inflation rate(%) 5.5 - 7.0 6.4   \par \par \uc2 Interest rate(%) 8.4 - 9.0 8 - 8.84 (3-month BI)   \par \par \uc2 Exchange rate(Rp) 8,400 - 8,700 8,000 - 8,300   \par \par \uc2 Open unemployment (millions) 10.5-10.8 ---   \par \par \uc2 Population Below Poverty Line (%) 17.7-18.0   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020031223dzco0000a\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
