\par\par \b \uc2 Taxing kampong dwellers to relieve the blight   \b0\par\par\uc2 943 \uc2 words\par \uc2 27 December 2003\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 2\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2003 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Growing slum areas and evictions in Jakarta have prompted some urban architects to further promote concepts of urban development that involve the local communities. Scholars from Delft University of Technology in Delft, the Netherlands, Jakarta's Erasmus Huis and other academics recently held a workshop involving young urban architects.   \par \par \uc2 One of the organizers, H. Juergen Rosemann, a professor at the Delft School of Architecture, shared some of his views with The Jakarta Post's Evi Mariani.   \par \par \uc2 Question: What should be done with cities in Indonesia, particularly Jakarta, to improve slum areas, or kampongs   \par \par \uc2 Answer: During our discussions here it has become clear that the main threat regarding the kampongs is that they have been identified as slums. Of course they have the characteristics of slums, like poor people living there, poor living conditions, with problematic waste and sewage disposal.   \par \par \uc2 Therefore, people think such areas are temporary, and it means nobody takes care, nobody invests, nobody improves the infrastructure or sanitation, for example.   \par \par \uc2 These areas are a source of activity. There are marketplaces and a lot of people produce things.   \par \par \uc2 So a change of mind is necessary -- to explore the kampong areas not only as slums or deteriorated areas but also as areas with a certain potential. They could be developed and have better qualities, particularly for people living there. With that in mind, the kampongs would be seen as places that need to be sustained, not just temporary locations. Who do you think should invest in the kampongs?   \par \par \uc2 The main investment, the main improvement, should be done by the people themselves. But the government could help in a very effective way by making these areas really permanent.   \par \par \uc2 The government should ensure that land use will not be changed, that developers will not take over the land.   \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  on the part of the government is one big threat for these areas. That could be the important point of the government to provide security and certainty.   \par \par \uc2 And at a relatively low cost, the infrastructure can be improved profoundly, for example by implementing better sewage and garbage disposal.   \par \par \uc2 The people could improve their quality of life by themselves, but under these conditions: The improvement of the infrastructure and certainty of their future from the government. Have you ever been to a kampong in Jakarta?   \par \par \uc2 Once this week, I visited (Bukit Duri in South Jakarta) and talked with the people. I can compare it with slum areas in Latin America like in Rio de Janeiro and Sao Paulo and I think the kampongs in Jakarta have much more hope because they are less deteriorated and they have integrated \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  factors much more than the favelas have in Latin America.   \par \par \uc2 I was really impressed by the possibilities the kampongs here have. From what I've seen, people support each other, they work together. It was a complete and functioning community.   \par \par \uc2 There are street vendors and small shops. But they do not only sell things, they produce things and there is an astonishing range of products. And I call that the potential of kampongs. How do you see the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  of the City administration, which is evicting people from slum areas, then building low-cost apartments and forcing them to move to those apartments?   \par \par \uc2 In general, in a segregated city, relocating people to other areas is only relocating problems. And the problem will increase because the people who are replaced lose their social network, and then they have to build up a whole new environment.   \par \par \uc2 Relocation should be avoided as much as possible. Of course, sometimes it's not possible. Jakarta, a city that depends on powerful \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development, has to provide space for it, otherwise it will become a city only of the poor.   \par \par \uc2 But particularly for the traditional kampong, it's important not to destroy them because it will only increase social problems like criminality and vandalism.   \par \par \uc2 But not only that. There's some interesting research in the United States and Europe. The conclusion was that a city that is more integrated, with less of a gap between the poor and the rich, has more advantages in \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  terms.   \par \par \uc2 The research concluded that to support integration means, in fact, to support the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 In Jakarta, you have a formal \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and an informal \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The big part is the informal one. The income of the government is only based on the formal \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Having a weak formal \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and strong informal \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  means you have a poor government.   \par \par \uc2 And that means the government has no money to develop facilities like \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  transportation or an underground transit system. They have no money to prevent floods.   \par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, people from the informal sector do not really participate in the development of infrastructure because they don't pay \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2 . But, of course, rich people also gain more advantages from the highly segregated situation as they can hire people, paying for services at low cost.   \par \par \uc2 This highly segregated situation also can be seen this way: The government does not have much money for infrastructure, so we see enormous traffic jams each day.   \par \par \uc2 So lack of infrastructure is threatening, and limits the city's development.   \par \par \uc2 Even though the urban poor don't pay \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2 , could they at least improve their own surroundings?   \par \par \uc2 Yes, they can improve their situation. And improving themselves means that at a certain moment they can grow from the informal to the formal \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 But the important point is, the improvement should be supported by the government by creating stable circumstances.   \par \par \uc2 Once the government can assure the certainty of their future in the kampong, they can produce more, and in return pay \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020031226dzcr00003\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
