\par\par \b \uc2 GDP growth to remain low for 2-3 years: Economists   \b0\par\par\uc2 Leony Aurora, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta   \par \uc2 577 \uc2 words\par \uc2 21 January 2004\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 13\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2004 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Indonesia has been trapped in low \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth rates for seven years and is likely to stay there in the next two to three years because of continued lack of investment, analysts said.   \par \par \uc2 Speaking in a discussion on the political and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  outlook for 2004 on Tuesday, economist Faisal Basri said that the annual Gross Domestic Product (GDP) growth had stayed at an average rate of less than 4 percent over the past few years.   \par \par \uc2 After the initial hit of the 1997 financial crisis, GDP growth plummeted to minus 13.2 percent in 1998. Although the figure bounced to a little above zero the following year, it remained low and last year's was estimated at 3.9 percent.   \par \par \uc2 "Consumption had been the only driving factor for growth (during the past years)," said Faisal. "The upcoming elections will bring higher consumption, with parties \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  money for campaigning," he added.   \par \par \uc2 But investment, a key ingredient to achieve higher and sustainable growth, remains low due to various \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  at home and overseas.   \par \par \uc2 The Investment Coordinating Board (BKPM) reported that the approved FDI in 2003 was US$13.21 billion, a jump from 2002's figure of $9.79 billion. Unfortunately most of it came from expansion of existing projects and changes in status of firms from local to foreign and only $5 billion worth of projects was completely new.   \par \par \uc2 Of the approved FDI, $4.97 billion was realized.   \par \par \uc2 An economist from the University of Indonesia, Muhammad Chatib Basri, pointed out that investors would not come this year due to the protracted six-month general election period.   \par \par \uc2 "Old investors will stay because they are already used to the situation here, but new ones will wait," he said.   \par \par \uc2 About 145 million voters will elect their representatives in April and their president in July. If none of the presidential candidates achieve more than 50 percent of the vote, another round is set in September.   \par \par \uc2 "After observing the performance of the elected government for six months or more, new investments may come in the second semester of 2005," said Chatib. "Its effects will be felt in 2007."   \par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, domestic investment rose by 92 percent to Rp 48.48 trillion last year as compared to 2002, BKPM said.   \par \par \uc2 Despite aggressive efforts by \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  to cut its benchmark interest rate, banks remain reluctant to boost lending to the corporate sector amid remaining high \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the sector.   \par \par \uc2 Loan to deposit ratio of the country's banking industry stood at 52 percent in August last year.   \par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 's benchmark interest rate has gone down to around 8.06 percent from over 13 percent earlier last year. But the lending rate remained stubbornly high at around 17 percent earlier in January this year.   \par \par \uc2 But Chatib said that the lack of bank financing availability was also due to funding mismatch problems in the industry as people still doubt local banks as reflected by the fact that 60 percent of time deposits were short-term one-month deposits.   \par \par \uc2 "How can long-term loans be funded by short-term funds?" he said.   \par \par \uc2 The government is targeting an \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth of 4.8 percent this year, while most private think-tanks forecast a GDP growth of around 4.4 percent.   \par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  has to grow by around 6 percent to 7 percent per year in order to absorb the millions of unemployed.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020040120e01l0001d\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
