\par\par \b \uc2 New visa  \highlight22\uc2 policy \highlight\uc2  casts dark cloud over ailing Bali tourist industry   \b0\par\par\uc2 Jenny H. Backstrom, Contributor, Kuta, Bali   \par \uc2 984 \uc2 words\par \uc2 29 January 2004\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 2\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2004 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 It is still the rainy season in Bali. But other forms of clouds, confusion and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , currently cover the island.   \par \par \uc2 The hot topic causing this confusion is the much-debated new visa-on-arrival \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , to be effective Feb. 1.   \par \par \uc2 For Bali the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is a potential nightmare. The island's tourist industry has been trying to recover since the October 2002 bombing and the more recent threat of SARS in the region.   \par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , previously scheduled to take effect on Dec. 1, 2003, will restrict visa-free entry to tourists from only 11 countries -- instead of the present 48.   \par \par \uc2 The countries include Singapore, Thailand, the Philippines, Brunei Darussalam, Hong Kong, Macao, China, Peru and Morocco.   \par \par \uc2 The 21 nationalities that lose their visa-free status but are still able to apply for a 30-day visa on arrival include the United States, Britain, Canada, France, Switzerland, Italy, Germany, Taiwan, Japan, South Korea and Australia.   \par \par \uc2 The new \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  also cuts the length of stay in Indonesia for short-term visitors from 60 days to only 30 days with an optional US$10 payment for three-day visit and $25 for a 30-day visit.   \par \par \uc2 Visitors from the affected countries are by far the largest groups to visit Bali. Three of the countries -- Japan, followed by Australia and South Korea -- are the island's biggest tourist markets.   \par \par \uc2 With only three days left to its implementation, question marks still hang over the scheme. Which segments of the tourist market will be hit hardest by the \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2 ? What will the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  consequences be?   \par \par \uc2 Opinions on these matters vary.   \par \par \uc2 Association of Indonesian Tour and Travel Agents (ASITA) Bali chairman I Gusti Agung Prana said the government's decision was political and had to do with national pride and respect.   \par \par \uc2 The Bali provincial government supports the decree -- especially the reduced length of the visa. The visa, it says, will protect local people from being exploited by expatriates living in Bali without a business visa.   \par \par \uc2 However, most in the industry are against the additional visa fee, which they say is a transparent money-making scheme that will further discourage tourism.   \par \par \uc2 Bali Tourism Board (BTB) chairman Putu Agus Antara remarked: "The smell of politics spiced with other interests is strong."   \par \par \uc2 I Gde Pitana, the head of the Bali Tourism Agency, objects to the visa fee and the date of its implementation. The decision had nothing to do with \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and security issues as had been argued by Minister of Justice and Human Rights Yusril Ihza Mahendra, he said.   \par \par \uc2 Pitana said the new \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  would not increase security in Bali as 30 days was easily enough time to plan and carry out a terrorist attack, plus any threats were unlikely to come from outside Indonesia.   \par \par \uc2 "The timing is very bad," he said, adding that Bali was still suffering from the effects of travel warnings imposed on the island by Western countries after the Bali bombing.   \par \par \uc2 Two-thirds of total arrivals in Bali each year are tourists traveling on package deals and many of these are families who would perhaps find it difficult to pay $25 for each member, he said. Tourists will object to the extra costs, especially those who booked packages up to six months ago.   \par \par \uc2 However, Pitana does not believe that halving the visa to 30 days will have a big impact on tourism in Bali. Even before the Bali bomb in 2002 the average stay had been only 9.5 days, with the longest stay about 21 days.   \par \par \uc2 "Very, very few stay longer than 30 days, maybe less than 10 percent," he said.   \par \par \uc2 Tourists who usually stay the longest in Indonesia are backpackers and surfers.   \par \par \uc2 Pitana said that Bali needed "quality tourists" interested in culture, upmarket environments and \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  their money. Since surfers and backpackers did not fit into this category, losing some of them would not have a big impact financially on Bali.   \par \par \uc2 However, a walk around in \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  areas like Kuta, where every other motorbike seems to be equipped with board racks, suggests that Bali's long-term stay clientele would have to make a difference to the island's local \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 Antara said that while \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  travelers were a minority and often spent less money than other tourists, their money was of great importance. It usually went straight into the pockets of local people in small-scale businesses, he said.   \par \par \uc2 This is the case not only in Bali but also in other regions such as Sumatra, Java, Lombok and Sumbawa, to where longer-term visitors often travel.   \par \par \uc2 "Since we have a lot of poor people, the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  travelers are important," Antara said, adding that their role in Bali's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  was often played down.   \par \par \uc2 "Bali benefits from people staying longer," he said.   \par \par \uc2 "I believe we will lose these people."   \par \par \uc2 This is a shame, he said, because \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  travelers and families love Bali and may be more "loyal" than other tourists.   \par \par \uc2 "There is no logic behind the decision," he said.   \par \par \uc2 And indeed, it does seem illogical to implement a law likely to hit almost every segment of Bali's tourist market: Families and package deal tourists with the visa fee, surfers and backpackers with the limited stay, and expatriates with both.   \par \par \uc2 Up until the last meeting, it was expected that the visa law implementation would be postponed, Agung Prana said. "During a crisis like this we need all the segments of the tourist market."   \par \par \uc2 In the short-term Bali will lose visitors, maybe as many as 30 percent, but as time goes by and the clientele changes, the provincial government and tourism board predicts that tourist numbers will return to normal levels, he said.   \par \par \uc2 There will be an evaluation of the new \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  in six months. If indicators show that the market has been badly affected amendments will be a priority.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020040128e01t0002x\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
