\par\par \b \uc2 Battle in lending market getting fiercer   \b0\par\par\uc2 Burhanuddin Abe, Contributor, Jakarta   \par \uc2 1,064 \uc2 words\par \uc2 3 February 2004\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 17\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2004 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Many people dream of owning their own house and car. But to make this dream come true, they need a large sum of money at their disposal.   \par \par \uc2 Houses and cars have soared in price since the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis hit this country in mid-1997. The crisis caused banks to curb their lending to consumers and increase \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  considerably. As a result, for many the dream of owning houses and cars remained a dream.   \par \par \uc2 However, times change and now the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is showing signs of improvement, One indicator, the lower rate of \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  promissory notes -- better known as its Indonesian acronym SBI -- has led commercial banks to channel more resources into consumer loans.   \par \par \uc2 As the SBI interest rate dropped from 12.93 percent in January 2003 to 8.3 percent in late 2003, there was more room for commercial banks to further cut their \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 , including, of course, the rates imposed on consumer loans.   \par \par \uc2 Today, commercial banks appear to be engaged in a race to offer the lowest \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  for consumer loans. Take the home loan, or KPR, for example. In early 2003, the rates for home loans were still in the region of 17 to 20 percent per annum and not a single bank seemed willing to cut their \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 In May and July 2003, however, Bank Central Asia (BCA) slashed its home loan interest rate to 15 percent. BCA even offers a fixed interest rate of 12 percent per annum for the first year.   \par \par \uc2 Bank Central's move has compelled other banks to follow suit. Bank Niaga, Bank Permata, Bank NISP and Bank Mandiri are among large institutions that have also lowered \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  for home loans. Bank Tabungan Negara (the State Savings Bank, or BTN), which has for years been synonymous with property loans, has also cut its rates.   \par \par \uc2 At present, the \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  in home loan schemes range between 13 and 15 percent annually. This is a landmark as the rate had never before fallen to below 14 percent per annum. Even in the pre-monetary crisis period, the rate was always higher than 16 percent per annum.   \par \par \uc2 The present level of interest is favorable to consumers. That's why there has been a sharp jump in the demand for home loans in the past year. This year alone, Bank Central has allocated Rp 2 trillion to its home loan scheme, a 100 percent rise compared with the figure last year. The BTN, meanwhile, has set aside Rp 1.4 trillion (about US$164.7 million) for the same scheme, about a 15 percent increase on last year's Rp 1.2 trillion.   \par \par \uc2 Other banks will also focus on home loans. According to the Center for Indonesian Property Studies, this year \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 -owned banks will allocate a total of Rp 10 trillion for property loans, an increase of Rp 2 trillion on the figure recorded last year. This expansion is reason enough for banks with home loan schemes to compete in attracting customers. "Now is the right time for expansion. Unless we do it now, we will lose out to private banks," said a state bank official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.   \par \par \uc2 Private and state banks can freely compete with each other. The banks that win offer the lowest \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  and, with customer satisfaction in mind, provide excellent personalized services.   \par \par \uc2 Similarly tough competition is also taking place in car loan schemes (KPM). In this sector, banks are competing not only with each other but also with leasing companies. Currently, the interest rate for cars ranges between seven and 12 percent for a loan-repayment period of between one and five years.   \par \par \uc2 Just as with home loans, banks are putting more resources into car loans this year. The Info Bank Research Bureau calculated the funds allocated for such loan schemes would reach Rp 100 trillion this year.   \par \par \uc2 It is only natural banks are interested in boosting their KPM schemes. While the national \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is still somewhat sluggish, channeling funds into consumer loans, such as KPMs, will be more profitable than providing loans for investment and working capital to businesses. In the consumer sector the likelihood these loans will turn into bad debts is quite small. This is the likely reason why Bank Bumi Putera has decided to issue bonds worth Rp 300 billion to expand its KPM scheme.   \par \par \uc2 Figures show resources put into consumer loans from 1999 to last year have soared, registering an average growth rate of 42.99 percent annually. This growth rate was much faster than for investment and working capital loans. During that period loans for investment grew by only 11.96 percent -- to Rp 90.6 trillion. As for working capital loans, they increased 55 percent from Rp 143.4 trillion in 1999 to Rp 222.8 trillion last year -- an increase of only 11.70 percent annually.   \par \par \uc2 The same research shows the growth in consumer loans is likely to continue this year. Car loans and other forms of consumer loans -- credit cards, non-collateral loans and home and apartment loans -- are predicted to amount to Rp 150 trillion in the consumer loans market.   \par \par \uc2 The jump in the growth of consumer loans is attributable to several things. The corporate sector needs more time to grow as its loan-restructuring is yet to run smoothly. The investment sector also continues to stagnate because of a slowly recovering \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and suspicions about the judiciary, employee quality and political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, the consumer sector is first to grow and to be relatively unaffected by the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis. Banks have eased further the requirements for the approval of consumer loans, not only for home and car ownership, but also in the case of non-collateral loans.   \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth has been spurred mostly by consumers so it is only natural increased liquidity will result.   \par \par \uc2 Obviously, the tight competition between banks over KPRs and KPMs is to the benefit of their customers. Hence, more and more people are likely to realize their dream of owning their own house and car.   \par \par \uc2 Still, customers must always be on the alert and must not let themselves be lured by banks into taking loans that turn into an unbearable burden.   \par \par \uc2 They don't want to turn into bad debtors -- like some of their counterparts in the business world.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020040202e02300013\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
