\par\par \b \uc2 The future of democracy in Indonesia  \b0\par\par\uc2 The future of democracy in Indonesia  \par \uc2 1,323 \uc2 words\par \uc2 5 February 2004\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 7\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2004 The Jakarta Post  \par \par \uc2 Baladas Ghoshal, Professor of Southeast Asian Studies, Jawaharlal Nehru University, New Delhi  \par \par \uc2 Indonesia's transition to democracy in the post-Soeharto era has evoked various responses and reactions from outsiders and Indonesians alike. The outsiders, particularly its neighbors, fear the knock-on effects of prolonged political instability in Indonesia. Thus they treat it indulgently not so much of its strength but of its weakness, and of the specters that evokes: In the short term, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  stagnation; in the long term, waves of refugees, pirate-infested seas and a power vacuum.  \par \par \uc2 More important, however, is what the Indonesians think of their country's progress toward democracy. Indonesians' reactions vary from cautious optimism to apathy and fatalism to utter cynicism. Also a belief that a great opportunity to bring about real social, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and political transformation of their society has been wasted for once and for all, and finally some feel a nostalgia for the days of order and stability of the Soeharto era.  \par \par \uc2 While there are different shades and nuances in the thinking of the political publics in Indonesia, for the sake of convenience, I would divide them into two categories: Radical reformers and cautious pragmatists. They differ on the question of the actual progress of democratic governance and the method through which such transition need to be handled. The former yearn for more radical reforms and transformation of their society and sometimes one can hear the echo of Sukarno (Revolusi belum selesai -- The revolution has yet to be completed) in their lamentation Reformasi belum selesai (The reformation has yet to be completed). The latter support an incremental process in the transition towards democracy. They have one thing in common: Neither of them wants a reversal of the existing process towards democratization and restoration of the old authoritarian system.  \par \par \uc2 Worrisome are the ones who have begun to feel nostalgic about the order and certainty of the old regime, and in a new garb making a desperate bid to come back to power again. Members of the old regime are currently weak but are not dead, thus can take advantage of the current political and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  to make a bid for power in the name of stability and development.  \par \par \uc2 Gen. Wiranto has already emerged as a strong candidate for presidency from Golkar, and if Akbar Tanjung loses in his appeal to the Supreme Court for rejecting his conviction in the corruption scandal, the former is sure to emerge as the nominee of the party. The emergence of PKPB (Concern for the Nation Functional Party) led former army chief R. Hartono and its nomination of Soeharto's eldest daughter, Siti "Tutut" Hardiyanti Rukmana as their Presidential candidate is another sign of the New Order to return. Earlier they were moving scrumptiously, but now they are all in the open. They still have their money and remnants of organizational power.  \par \par \uc2 To what direction Indonesia is moving? Soeharto's downfall in May 1998 was celebrated as heralding the birth of a "new Indonesia", and a "second independence" from the oppressive rule of their own ruler and its worst manifestations in the form of "cronyism, corruption and collusion" (KKN). The change brought rising expectations and hope that it would usher Indonesia towards democracy, good governance, transparency and accountability of its new leaders. Now after more than five years of the changeover the rising expectations continues.  \par \par \uc2 However, the hope for democracy and good governance is dimming as the people witness the greed, hypocrisy, hunger for power, horse-trading, corruption of the new power elites and the slide of the country towards further political, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2 , ethnic and religious turmoil halting the movement towards demilitarizing its society and establishing democracy in the country.  \par \par \uc2 Cynicism pervades the broad spectrum of the political publics about the current President Megawati's ability to provide the necessary leadership in such times of crisis and to rule the country, as well as regarding her commitment towards furthering the process of democratic reform. Former student activists who took part in rallies that contributed to the forced resignation of Soeharto openly voice their disappointment and frustration with the new political elites who took the place of the old and suggest that "reform created 'new thieves' who took advantage after the downfall of Soeharto".  \par \par \uc2 From the perspective of the reformers, besides the emergence of "new thieves", the "old thieves," and the corruptors in the new order era of Soeharto are still maintaining their important positions in the government, \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  bodies and judiciary. They have become disillusioned since the government of Megawati and the former President Abdurrahman Wahid displayed no strong commitment to uncover human rights violations, mainly committed by the TNI.  \par \par \uc2 There is widespread feeling amongst the reformers and even amongst her own supporters that Megawati, once a popular opposition leader, has developed signs of authoritarianism and traits of aloofness during her one year and a nine months as the nation's leader, a tendency that could undermine democracy. Megawati's overwhelming victory in the 1999 elections was possible essentially because she was seen by many as a rallying point of opposition to then president Soeharto's new order.  \par \par \uc2 She was a silent symbol of Soeharto's victim of his authoritarian and repressive regime, particularly manifested in the so-called July 27 affair of 1996. Megawati's current policies as well as those of her party are viewed by many as betrayal of the very people, the common man, that have voted her, though not directly, to the presidency. Instead of keeping alive the spirit of reformasi that calls for greater transparency and \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  participation in the political decision-making process, Megawati has been accused of engaging in backroom deals and horse-trading.  \par \par \uc2 Authoritarian political institutions that broke down under the pressure of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  collapse and social turmoil has been replaced now with institutions that are either very weak to establish order and legitimacy, or like the newly assertive parliament whose members by and large are viewed by the people as self-aggrandizing and unrepresentative of popular aspirations and their democratic impulses. Many of them are carry-over from the old regime of Soeharto, who have now joined the bandwagon of democracy by wearing a new color.  \par \par \uc2 The systematic depoliticization and the total emasculation of the civil society undertaken during the Soeharto years made it difficult for the other social forces who would have loved to have a more participatory system of governance but did not have the organizational apparatus and the ideological framework to take advantage of the opening up of the new democratic space.  \par \par \uc2 The old elites of the authoritarian era were better positioned to fill the vacuum by virtue of their access to money and organizational power. With the institutions of democracy they have now been able to have their positions even more consolidated than in the past. Instead of one Soeharto, there are now many "mini-Soeharto" seeking rent from the state.  \par \par \uc2 The cautious pragmatists point to the gains made in the last five years to the incremental process toward democracy, a free and vibrant press, individual freedom, constitutional amendments, particularly the direct presidential elections, freedom to form political parties, creation of Constitutional Court and many statutory bodies to oversee and provide checks and balances to the activities of the state. They underline the significant scaling down of the political role of the armed forces, and more importantly the newly-acquired power of the parliament and the exposure of the office of the President to \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  scrutiny.  \par \par \uc2 Furthermore, they also try to argue that democratic transition in any country is always fraught with stress, strains and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 , and can never be expected to be smooth and orderly!  \par \par \uc2 The writer has just completed an assignment for the United Nations Support Facility for Indonesian Recovery (UNSFIR) to study the political process towards democracy in Indonesia. He has prepared this article exclusively for The Jakarta Post.  \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020040204e0250000r\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
