ction period.   \par \par \uc2 The weak investment flow has affected the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  which has been growing at a meager rate of less than 4 percent during the past couple of years as growth has been largely driven by domestic consumption while exports and investments remained slow.   \par \par \uc2 Economists have said that the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  needs to return to its pre-crisis growth level of between 6 percent and 7 percent in order to be able to provide enough jobs for the millions of unemployed.   \par \par \uc2 Elsewhere, BKPM said that the food sector had attracted the most attention from foreign investors during the month of January, followed by the construction, and chemical and pharmacy industries.   \par \par \uc2 Banten Province was the most favored investment place attracting some $101.7 million in approved FDI. In second place was Gorontalo, which saw an FDI figure of $85.5 million. The densely populated West Java province was in third place with FDI figure of $21.2 million.   \par \par \uc2 England was the largest source of the FDI in January, followed by Brazil and Japan.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020040216e02h0001c\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
