\par\par \b \uc2 Buoyed by IMF praise   \b0\par\par\uc2 809 \uc2 words\par \uc2 10 March 2004\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2004 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 The government, still rejoicing over the exceedingly positive market reception of its first global bond offering in over seven years, got another dose of high praise from the International Monetary Fund, which completed last week its review of Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies and performance under its surveillance mechanism (Article IV).   \par \par \uc2 The annual surveillance review, which was conducted in conjunction with the first \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  discussion under the IMF Post-Program Monitoring arrangement Indonesia entered into in January after the end of the IMF extended facility in December, was full of commendations for the government for its \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 -reform performance.   \par \par \uc2 The IMF cited significant progress in the implementation of reform measures, as stipulated in the September 2003 White Paper, and pointed to the positive \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  indicators in key areas such as low inflation, a steady decline in interest rate, a stable rupiah exchange rate and the increase in international \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 It praised the government's determination to continue its \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  consolidation to reduce the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  to as low as 1.3 percent of gross domestic product this year from 2.1 percent last year. So buoyed was the IMF team with the positive \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  trends that it projected that \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth this year would hit 4.8 percent, up from an annual average of around 4 percent in the 2001-2003 period.   \par \par \uc2 Different from past \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reviews between 1998 and 2003 when the country was still under the IMF extended facility arrangement (bailout program), the latest review and \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  discussions were not legally binding because the assessment was not tied to loan disbursements from the IMF.   \par \par \uc2 However, the findings and recommendations resulting from the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  review and discussions with the IMF remain greatly influential in shaping market perception and credibility of the government and so too, consequently, Indonesia's sovereign risks and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  prospects.   \par \par \uc2 It is therefore well-advised for the government not to be lulled into complacency with a lackadaisical attitude, assuming that the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis is now all over and the country is in for some robust growth, especially because the IMF qualified its commendations with a series of \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  recommendations.   \par \par \uc2 Take for example, the warning offered by the IMF team at a meeting with the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 's board of directors last Thursday. The IMF expressed great concern that several banks had been engaged in unsound lending sprees that could threaten the viability of the whole industry, which is still fragile. The IMF team also urged the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  to improve its banking supervision capability and effectiveness and to be more forceful in enforcing its directives and rules on banks.   \par \par \uc2 Though many might be surprised by the IMF's strong advice against overly aggressive lending, but it is because total loan growth last year remained virtually stagnant vis a vis the 2002 expansion rate of around 19 percent. Additionally, the loan-to-deposit-ratio within the industry was still very low at about 50 percent, so an early warning is very important to prevent another debacle in the banking industry.   \par \par \uc2 It is likely that the IMF warning was directed especially at the "go-go" consumer lending by several banks. The fierce competition in and the expansion of consumer loans, which exceeded 66 percent in 2000 and 45 percent in 2001 and remained inordinately high at 37 percent in 2002 and 32 percent in 2003, could indeed threaten another upsurge in non-performing loans within the financial services industry.   \par \par \uc2 Other \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  recommendations, as stipulated in the 12-paragraph press statement issued at the end of the IMF review on Friday was an urge for the government to tackle weaknesses in \b \highlight22\uc2 taxation\b0 \highlight\uc2  and customs service regulations, enhancing labor market flexibility and addressing problems with property rights and contract enforcement. Without significant and quick progress in these reform measures, Indonesia's growth rate will remain lower than that of most other countries in Asia.   \par \par \uc2 The press release devoted two paragraphs to \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  recommendations on \b \highlight22\uc2 taxation\b0 \highlight\uc2  and customs services. Progress in these two areas has been seen by most analysts and businesspeople as far too slow and way short of what is needed to reduce the costs of doing business and to stimulate investment in the country.   \par \par \uc2 The amendment of the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  laws are also way behind schedule. Most businesspeople and analysts are worried that the draft amendments prepared by the government are far from adequate to remove \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and minimize corruption within the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  department.   \par \par \uc2 The IMF team explicitly cited weaknesses in arbitrary \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  assessments, inefficiencies in the refund system for the value added \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  and income \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  and burdensome customs procedures as major barriers to investment.   \par \par \uc2 Failure to make significant progress in the reform of \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  and customs service and labor rules could further postpone the return of foreign direct investors, even if the upcoming elections go off without a hitch this year.   \par \par \uc2 ______   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020040309e03a0000t\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
