\par\par \b \uc2 How to deal with  \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty \highlight\uc2  with insecurity and freedom   \b0\par\par\uc2 Ralf Dahrendorf , Former Rector, London School of Economics Project Syndicate   \par \uc2 846 \uc2 words\par \uc2 13 April 2004\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 7\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2004 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 I have often wondered why Karl Popper ended the dramatic peroration of the first volume of his Open Society and Its Enemies with the sentence: "We must go on into the unknown, the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  and insecure, using what reason we have to plan for both security and freedom." Is not freedom enough? Why put security on the same level as that supreme value?   \par \par \uc2 Then one remembers that Popper was writing in the final years of World War II. Looking around the world in 2004, you begin to understand Popper's motive: Freedom always means living with risk, but without security, risk means only threats, not opportunities.   \par \par \uc2 Examples abound. Things in Iraq may not be as bad as the daily news of bomb attacks make events there sound; but it is clear that there will be no lasting progress towards a liberal order in that country without basic security. Afghanistan's story is even more complex, though the same is true there. But who provides security, and how?   \par \par \uc2 In Europe and the West, there is the string of terrorist acts -- from those on the U.S. in 2001 to the pre-election bombings in Madrid -- to think about. London's Mayor and police chief have jointly warned that terrorist attacks in the city are "inevitable." Almost every day there are new warnings, with heavily armed policemen in the streets, concrete barriers appearing in front of embassies and \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  buildings, stricter controls at airports and elsewhere -- each a daily reminder of the insecurity that surrounds us.   \par \par \uc2 Nor is it only bombs that add to life's general \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Gradually, awareness is setting in that global warming is not just a gloom and doom fantasy. Social changes add to such insecurities. All at once we seem to hear two demographic time-bombs ticking: The continuing population explosion in parts of the third world, and the astonishing rate of aging in the first world. What will this mean for social \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 ? How will mass migration affect countries' cultural heritage?   \par \par \uc2 There is also a widespread sense of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  insecurity. No sooner is an upturn announced than it falters. At any rate, employment seems to have become decoupled from growth. Millions worry about their jobs -- and thus the quality of their lives -- in addition to fearing for their personal security.   \par \par \uc2 Such examples serve to show that the most disquieting aspect of today's insecurity may well be the diversity of its sources, and that there are no clear explanations and simple solutions. Even a formula like "war on terror" simplifies a more complex phenomenon.   \par \par \uc2 So what should we do? Perhaps we should look at Popper again and remember his advice: to use what reason we have to tackle our insecurities.   \par \par \uc2 In many cases this requires drastic measures, particularly insofar as our physical security is concerned. But while it is hard to deny that such measures are necessary, it is no less necessary to remember the other half of the phrase: "Security and freedom."   \par \par \uc2 Checks on security measures that curtail the freedoms that give our lives dignity are as imperative as protection. Such checks can take many forms. One is to make all such measures temporary by giving these new laws and regulations "sunset clauses" that limit their duration. Security must not become a pretext for the suspending and destroying the liberal order.   \par \par \uc2 A second requirement is that we look ahead more effectively. It is not necessary for us to wait for great catastrophes to occur if we can see them coming. Holland does not have to sink into the North Sea before we do something about the world's climate; pensions do not have to decline to near-zero before social policies are adjusted.   \par \par \uc2 A third need is to preserve, and in many cases to recreate, what one might call islands of security. Globalization must become "glocalization": There is value in the relative certainties of local communities, small companies, human associations. Such islands are not sheltered and protected spaces, but models for others. They prove that up to a point security can be provided without loss of freedom.   \par \par \uc2 There remains the most fundamental issue of attitude. It is debatable whether governments should ever frighten their citizens by painting the horror scenario of "inevitable" attack. The truth -- to quote Popper again -- is that "we must go on into the unknown, the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  and insecure," come what may.   \par \par \uc2 Today's instabilities may be unusually varied and severe, but human life is one of ceaseless \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  at all times. Such \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  can lead to a frozen state of near-entropy. More frequently, \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  leads to someone claiming to know how to eliminate it -- frequently through arbitrary powers that benefit but a few.   \par \par \uc2 False gods have always profited from a widespread sense of insecurity. Against them, an active effort to tackle the risks around us is the only answer. Perhaps we need a new Enlightenment to spread the confidence we need to live with insecurity in freedom.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020040412e04d0000w\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex1