\par\par \b \uc2 World Bank sees growth but new investment unlikely   \b0\par\par\uc2 Dadan Wijaksana , The Jakarta Post, Jakarta   \par \uc2 528 \uc2 words\par \uc2 21 April 2004\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 3\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2004 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 The World Bank said Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  could grow faster this year thanks to a better global trade picture, but warned of poor performance in the investment sector.   \par \par \uc2 The Bank, in its biannual assessment report on the region's economies, predicted the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to grow by 4.5 percent in 2004, 0.5 percent higher than its initial prediction last year.   \par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  grew by 4.1 percent in 2003, the Bank noted, slightly outpacing the government's target of 4 percent.   \par \par \uc2 The report also urged the government to accelerate efforts to boost exports and investment, as "growth remains consumption-driven, with exports and investment underperforming compared to other Asian countries".   \par \par \uc2 "For Indonesia, the key challenge remains accelerating growth. Turning this around requires improving the investment climate and improving Indonesia's competitiveness," said Bert Hofman, the Bank's lead economist in Indonesia.   \par \par \uc2 On investment, the Bank said the country was still struggling to recover to the pre-crisis level in terms of luring investors to the country. The current contribution of investment to the gross domestic product (GDP) is 10 percent under the pre-crisis level.   \par \par \uc2 "Fixed capital formation grew by a meager 1.4 percent in 2003, and the share of investment in GDP declined from 20.3 percent in 2002 to 19.7 percent in 2003," said the report, and that the condition had dragged down efforts to reduce unemployment and poverty.   \par \par \uc2 Citing official data, the Bank said between May 2002 and February 2003 alone, 400,000 Indonesians became unemployed due to the meager \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. Unemployment was on the rise and reached 8.5 percent in August last year.   \par \par \uc2 The number of jobs in the formal sector is also declining, which means that more people have been absorbed by the informal sector.   \par \par \uc2 "The share of the informal sector employment increased from 54 percent in 1997 to 64 percent in 2002," said the Bank.   \par \par \uc2 Numerous analyses have shown that the country's investment climate will not improve unless integrated efforts in various areas are made. Included in this must-do list of actions are: ensuring stability, fixing the corrupt judiciary, easing worker-employer disputes and resolving post-autonomy confusion.   \par \par \uc2 Adding to its concerns is the general election, as "\b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  on an incoming government will not be resolved until the end of the year. A recovery in investment this year, therefore, remains unlikely".   \par \par \uc2 The country held its \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  election on April 5, which will be followed by its first direct presidential election on July 5, with a strong possibility of a runoff in September.   \par \par \uc2 Despite the gloomy outlook in investment, the country has regained some ground in its macroeconomic performance.   \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Public\b0 \highlight\uc2  debt fell in the past five years to around 69 percent of the GDP, with external debt estimated at US$135 billion, or 70 percent of the GDP compared, with 80 percent in 2002.   \par \par \uc2 Having graduated from a special lending program under the International Monetary Fund (IMF) in December 2003, the nation successfully launched $1 billion in sovereign bonds, in what analysts said was a reflection of an increasing investors' confidence.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020040420e04l0000a\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 The World Bank: The Percentage of Indonesian Poor People Reach Only 6%  \b0\par\par\uc2 359 \uc2 words\par \uc2 27 April 2004\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2004 Bisnis Indonesia  \par \par \uc2 The World Bank reports that the number of the Eastern Asians living below the extreme poverty line (under US$1/day) falls drastically. Indonesia, for example, manages to reduce its percentage of the poor people from 20.6% in 1990 to 6.2%.  \par \par \uc2 In the World Bank's report entitled the World Development Indicators 2004, the percentage of the Eastern Asians living below the poverty line, compared to the global population, drops from 40% in 1981 to 21% in 2001.  \par \par \uc2 China, the main \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth motor in Asia, can raise 150 million people living below the poverty line in 2001.  \par \par \uc2 The report spark controversy as data in Indonesian revealed that the poverty rate didn't improve. Rather, the unemployment rate even reaches 40 million people.  \par \par \uc2 According to Francois Bourguignon, economist with the World Bank, the first goal of the Millenium Development Goal approved by 189 countries in 2000 was to reduce the poverty rate by an half from 1990 to 2015. Several countries, he added, had noted some remarkable successes.  \par \par \uc2 "However, several regions have not showed sustainable growth," he informed.  \par \par \uc2 According to a chief economist, Emil Salim, Indonesia was actually able to make benefit out of the 'glory era' of Asia in 2005-2015 by maintaining political situation and stability.  \par \par \uc2 By 2015, he said, Indonesia should no longer worry about the poor people population and the creation of jobs.  \par \par \uc2 Doesn't have to be pro-market  \par \par \uc2 Emil, therefore, argued that the presidential election didn't necessarily have to produce a cabinet that submitted to market policies.  \par \par \uc2 The general election this year, he added, should come up with \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 -makers who could provide legal certainties for the businesses.  \par \par \uc2 Emil hoped after the election, politicians would put more focus on development.  \par \par \uc2 He suggested politicians learn from the cabinet situation after the previous general election in 1999 since such situation only led to political chaos and legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 .  \par \par \uc2 If they failed to learn, Emil continued, the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth would be way behind China (9.1%), or Malaysia (5.2%), Thailand (6.7%), and Vietnam (7.2%) in 2003. (luz)  \par \par \uc2 Document BISNIS0020040427e04r00002\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
