\par\par \b \uc2 Open letter to the next President of Indonesia   \b0\par\par\uc2 Kahlil Rowter , Jakarta   \par \uc2 1,274 \uc2 words\par \uc2 29 April 2004\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2004 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 I congratulate you on becoming the leader of the fourth most populous country on earth and the third largest democracy in history. As the first president to be elected directly, you carry the mandate and the hopes of more than 230 million on your shoulders. I do not envy you in this regard. History will judge you harshly, and the media even more so. But your taskmaster is not the press, nor history, but the plight of your people -- even those who did not vote for you.   \par \par \uc2 Your election could not come at a more critical time. Indonesia has only begun to recover from its severe \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  downturn. It is undeniable that the worst phases of the crisis are over, as attested to by most \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  indicators. In fact, we are now well into the recovery phase. But as regards sentiment or climate, I still hear people talk about and breathe the air of crisis.   \par \par \uc2 Perhaps that is just how we Indonesians go about it: We never really collapsed during the worst phases of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis, but we never really -- at least, not yet -- seem to shake off the feeling of being in a crisis.   \par \par \uc2 This may be your greatest challenge: How to imbue the average Indonesian with enthusiasm. If you fail, a ceiling of about 4 to 5 percent will be created over our \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. At this rate, job growth would be inadequate to absorb annual entrants into the labor market, thus resulting in rising unemployment. The unemployment figure as of August 2003 was 8.5 percent, significantly higher than just 9 months earlier in November 2002 at 8.1 percent. Although the statistics are not robust, the trend is undeniable: Unemployment is rising fast.   \par \par \uc2 Until now, the unemployed could rely on the culture of familial support peculiar to Indonesia, in which parents still welcome grown children to live at home. Even married couples with children can count on immediate and extended family support -- one contributing reason for the rise in the educated unemployed. But there has to be a breaking point sometime.   \par \par \uc2 Why is enthusiasm so important? The future is a product of effort and circumstances combined, and projections of the future drive how much effort to invest in the present. Hence, optimism plays a key role. The more optimistic one is, the more effort one can make now for a better tomorrow; the more effort made in the present, the better the chances for a positive outcome. Conversely, less effort will stultify the chances for success in the future, as if to justify the pessimism that was its cause.   \par \par \uc2 Investment, as with any other risky venture, is crucially determined by expectations of future outcomes. Take the price of equity, for example -- once the market is convinced that a particular firm will grow above a certain threshold, its price rises. But if this hope is betrayed, punishment is swift, and it will take more effort in convincing the market that the firm will reassume an upward growth trend. The same logic also applies to other endeavors in investment.   \par \par \uc2 One particularly vexing problem that harms raising expectations has been corruption, especially in the legal justice system. More broadly, this has resulted in a perception of legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and problematic contract enforcement.   \par \par \uc2 This is just one of the issues raised in a recent post-IMF program assessment on the existing \b \highlight22\uc2 economic policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Two other important issues are revamping the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  system and increasing labor market flexibility.   \par \par \uc2 It is well known that the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  office, with its rather arbitrary assessment methods and cumbersome refund system, creates unnecessary business \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Try asking how many of your frequent-flyer friends have recently received \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  returns on their "\b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2 " charge, payable by residents each time they leave the country.   \par \par \uc2 The need to revamp the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  system also stems from the constraints that the government \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  faces. For example, 29 percent of total revenues are allocated to just three main expenditures: Domestic debt interest payments (14 percent), overseas debt interest payments (7 percent) and fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  (9 percent).   \par \par \uc2 These three are also the most sensitive to market fluctuations, domestic \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the exchange rate and global oil prices. To be specific, a 1 percent rate increase in the 3-month \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  promissory note will incur an additional interest payment of about Rp 2.3 trillion (US$270 million). In addition, to refinance maturing domestic debt in the next three years, the government is relying on market absorption of bond issuances.   \par \par \uc2 Hence, future growth in \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  rests crucially on the ability to increase \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  revenues without simply raising \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  -- an unwise recourse in an \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovering from recession.   \par \par \uc2 It should be noted that the government's debt burden in relation to its GDP has fallen dramatically from its peak in 2000 of almost 100 percent to below 70 percent in 2003. This was mainly accomplished by paying off loans at a faster rate than borrowing.   \par \par \uc2 But the still-high debt-to-GDP ratio, plus scheduled refinancing needs and the sensitivity of expenditures on market conditions, create a constraint on future \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2 , further compounded by the requirement to share revenues with regional governments. All in all, this means that the degree of freedom at the central government is limited. For instance, pump priming or the use of government \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  as a \b \highlight22\uc2 stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2  -- mostly by resorting to \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  financing -- is severely limited.   \par \par \uc2 At the same time, the currently improving \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  environment also places constraints on the future path of key variables. This is because the existing environment and subsequent reaction by \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  agents create a particular dynamic path from which it will be difficult to deviate in future.   \par \par \uc2 Take the historically low interest rate environment, which has induced agents to increasingly finance automobile and motorcycle purchases as well as property purchases by multiyear loans. Therefore, any adverse movement in \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  would hit them hard. Another case in point is the increasing exposure of institutional investors to the government bond market.   \par \par \uc2 In the past, any interest movement, especially upwards, would be reflected instantly in a higher income, due to their exposure to time deposits. But now, the movement along the yield curve to longer-term instruments also means higher sensitivity to interest rate fluctuations.   \par \par \uc2 An increase in the liquidity of government bond trading and a wider spectrum of investor types also brings with it a responsibility on the part of the government -- which benefits from lower issuance costs -- and the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  -- which will soon cut costs in monetary management through using government bonds as an instrument for open market operations -- to maintain market stability.   \par \par \uc2 These are just a few examples of the constraints that you will face once you start to formulate your \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  plan.   \par \par \uc2 Mr(s). President, the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  problems are well-known. The key issues and the constraints that you will face have been laid out here. Therefore, what your \b \highlight22\uc2 economic policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  should accomplish is quite clear. Beyond this, I hope it is equally clear that we need your leadership to uplift our spirits. What we want to see now is your positive and swift response.   \par \par \uc2 Please remember that the challenges you face are numerous and difficult. If they were not, a less capable leader would have solved them by now. I hope you have the necessary stamina and patience -- stamina to tackle the multidimensional challenges facing Indonesia, and a healthy dose of patience toward us.   \par \par \uc2 We are a rowdy bunch, but basically good at heart.   \par \par \uc2 The writer is Head of Research at Mandiri Sekuritas. The views expressed in the article are strictly personal.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020040505e04t000bv\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 RI's  \highlight22\uc2 Economic \highlight\uc2  Growth Rate The Lowest in Asia   \b0\par\par\uc2 451 \uc2 words\par \uc2 29 April 2004\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2004 Bisnis Indonesia   \par \par \uc2 The Asian Development Bank (ADB) estimates the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth of Indonesia in 2004 will be the lowest in Asia (4.5%), the region that will enjoy the most dynamic growth this year.   \par \par \uc2 The ADB-one of the biggest creditors in the Consultative Group for Indonesia (CGI)-announced that the powerful intra-regional trade and the increasing customer demands had propelled Asian \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth by 6.8% this year. China is the main motor of the growth in the region.   \par \par \uc2 "East and Southeast Asian regions are helped by increases in China import," said chief economist at ADB Ifzal Ali when explaining ADB report entitled Asian Development Outlook yesterday.   \par \par \uc2 Ifzal cited consumption as the second motor of growth in Asia. Increases in consumption happened in China, Indonesia, Malaysia, Philippine, and Thailand.   \par \par \uc2 The increases in consumption, he explained, were caused by expansive \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies and accommodative monetary policies that led to the lower interest rate.   \par \par \uc2 The report also underlined the importance of Asia to reform its trade and to maintain political stability in a bid to boost foreign direct investment.   \par \par \uc2 The slower growth rate in Indonesia was caused by the low foreign direct investment, argued chief economist at ADB for Indonesia Ramesh Subramaniam.   \par \par \uc2 Subramaniam said foreigners were reluctant to make investment due to legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 ; poor physical infrastructures and poor governance.   \par \par \uc2 Country Director of ADB for Indonesia David J. Green emphasized that rules in Indonesia were too flexible.   \par \par \uc2 Subramaniam revealed that the estimated Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth of 4.5% this year would not be able to reduce poverty rate, which in 2002 and 2003 reached 18.2% and 17.4%, respectively.   \par \par \uc2 Data by the ADB are different with the report by the World Bank launched last week. The latter report disclosed that the poverty rate in Indonesia had drastically fallen from the pre-crisis 20% to the current 6.2%.   \par \par \uc2 Surprised   \par \par \uc2 However, the ADB admitted it was surprised of knowing Indonesia could reach the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth rate of 4.1% last year amidst the widespread depression in some Asian countries caused by terrorist attacks, Iraq crisis, and SARS.   \par \par \uc2 Subramaniam assessed that the inflation rate in 2003 was at the good level 5.1%, while the interest rate drastically fell from 12% to 8/4%. In addition, in 2003, the rupiah exchange against the dollar was stable and the export increased.   \par \par \uc2 Separately, Daniel Lian, chief economist at Morgan Stanley for Southeast Asia, said the macroeconomic stability and the reduction of risk premium achieved in 2003 were not enough to indicate that one \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  has recorded a success.   \par \par \uc2 According to Lian, Indonesia required a more proactive leader to design a more effective long-term development plan. (gak)   \par \par \uc2 Document BISNIS0020040429e04t00001\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
