\par\par \b \uc2 Panic selling routs JSX   \b0\par\par\uc2 Rendi A. Witular , Jakarta   \par \uc2 482 \uc2 words\par \uc2 7 May 2004\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2004 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 The Jakarta stock market sank further on Thursday for the sixth straight session on panic selling due to a combination of negative domestic and regional issues, offsetting the record gains made last month.   \par \par \uc2 The Jakarta Composite Index fell by 1.57 percent or 11.965 points to 746.117 with 1.52 billion shares worth Rp 1.21 trillion (US$139 million) changing hands.   \par \par \uc2 In just six trading days since it booked a historic record of 818.15 on April 27, the Index has plunged by 60.07 points or 7.3 percent.   \par \par \uc2 Bluechip telecommunications firm PT Telekomunikasi Indonesia (Telkom), the bourse's largest counter, led Thursday's disaster by losing Rp 400 to close at Rp 7,500.   \par \par \uc2 Stock analyst Fendi Susiyanto of BNI Securities said that investors had set aside the positive news on corporate performance, and tracked down negative sentiment on political and security \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  ahead of the presidential election.   \par \par \uc2 "Most foreign investors were in panic selling mode following a string of security problems at home, such as the sectarian clashes in Ambon, Maluku, and the recent bombing in Pekanbaru, Riau, that killed two people," Fendi said.   \par \par \uc2 Fendi explained that foreign investors, who now account for 50 percent of the average daily transaction value on the market, were afraid that such problems would escalate ahead of the presidential election on July 5 and the runoff on Sept. 20.   \par \par \uc2 Foreign-based securities firms, such as JP Morgan and DBS Vickers, and local firm Bhakti Capital Indonesia, were the top sellers. JP Morgan sold Rp 218 billion worth of stocks, DBS Rp 165 billion and Bhakti Rp 108 billion.   \par \par \uc2 Foreign investors mostly invest in the country's market via JP Morgan and DBS.   \par \par \uc2 Fendi also said that China's plan to scale down its investment \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  so as to cool down its overheating \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  had dealt a blow to the region, including Indonesia, which might lose its recent export gains to China.   \par \par \uc2 Indonesian exports, which are expected to emerge as a major growth engine, have been increasingly tied to the sharp increase in demand from China.   \par \par \uc2 A slowdown in the Chinese \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , led by a sharp decline in commodity demand and prices, would hurt Indonesia relative to its peers in Southeast Asia.   \par \par \uc2 Stock analyst and president director of Kim Eng Securities, Mustofa, concurred with Fendi, saying that the plan by China for a slowdown, along with the recent plan by the U.S. Federal Reserve to gradually increase interest benchmark rates, had further fueled the already negative sentiment.   \par \par \uc2 "The Index will remain under pressure due to these problems, and is unlikely to pick up again until after the country has elected a new president," said Mustofa.   \par \par \uc2 "We simply don't expect the Index to reach 800 again before the presidential vote, which will ensure political and security certainty for the market," he said.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020040506e05700003\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
