\par\par \b \uc2 Six-year-old reform drive going nowhere, critics say  \b0\par\par\uc2 Kurniawan Hari, Jakarta  \par \uc2 646 \uc2 words\par \uc2 12 May 2004\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 2\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2004 The Jakarta Post  \par \par \uc2 Six years after the onset of the reform movement that was triggered by the death of four Trisakti University students in Jakarta in May 1998 at the hands of security personnel, the nation has yet to see substantial changes in political, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and social life, activists say.  \par \par \uc2 Student activists shared their concern on Tuesday about the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  in political, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and social affairs despite the nation's reform movement they were part of.  \par \par \uc2 Syafik Alielha, who was formerly an activist with anti-New Order student group City Forum (Forkot), said what had happened in the country over the past six years reflected the state's failure to uphold the reform agenda.  \par \par \uc2 Despite the lives lost in the shooting incidents and the subsequent riots in May 1998, he said, none of the perpetrators, let alone the masterminds, were brought to court.  \par \par \uc2 "The state has made a big mistake because it has not brought the perpetrators to court...This has set a bad precedent for our future," he told The Jakarta Post here.  \par \par \uc2 Syafik is now an activist with the Indonesian Youth Struggle Front (FPPI), a group that campaigns for democratization.  \par \par \uc2 Sayeb Junaidi, who was an activist with the Forum of Communication for Jakarta's Students Senate (FKSMJ) six years ago, underlined that most of policies adopted by the current government benefited the elite at the expense of people at the grass roots.  \par \par \uc2 Forkot and FKSMJ were among many student groups in Jakarta that dared to challenge the government of president Soeharto.  \par \par \uc2 Many other student groups staged rallies in cities across the country, demanding that Soeharto step down after 32 years in power and called for sweeping reforms.  \par \par \uc2 Soeharto quit just nine days after Elang Mulya Lesmana, Hafidhin Royan, Hendriawan Sie, and Herry Hartanto were killed in their peaceful struggle to put Soeharto's dictatorship to an end.  \par \par \uc2 The shooting incident on May 12 was followed by massive riots and looting, which subsided only on May 15. It was during the rioting that hundreds of Chinese-Indonesian women were allegedly raped.  \par \par \uc2 An independent investigation revealed that the riots occurred in a systematic pattern across Greater Jakarta. Students, still mourning, kept themselves from the streets.  \par \par \uc2 An ad hoc team set up by the National Commission on Human Rights declared in September last year that crimes against humanity were found during the May 1998 riots.  \par \par \uc2 However, further legal action on the case did not materialize because of opposition from the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the institution authorized to call for an ad hoc human rights tribunal.  \par \par \uc2 "Only the victims of the riots and their families still feel the agony while others have forgotten," Syafik said.  \par \par \uc2 He regretted the fact that the majority of people had short memories.  \par \par \uc2 "The emergence of Golkar Party as the winner of the general election clearly shows that," he said, referring to the Golkar which was the political machine of Soeharto's New Order government.  \par \par \uc2 He acknowledged there were some improvements in democracy, including the direct presidential election and the removal of the military and the police from the House -- which will become effective after October of this year.  \par \par \uc2 Unfortunately, he said, the adoption of the new political system was a formality without the empowering of civil society, which is important to ensure checks and balances are in place.  \par \par \uc2 "The new system is necessary but not sufficient," he said.  \par \par \uc2 He added that the failure of the reform movement was the failure of the whole nation, particularly the political elite who were unable to assure people at the grass roots of a better future.  \par \par \uc2 "The inability to show something promising to the people has made the people distrust civilian leaders," he added.  \par \par \uc2 "This situation has apparently helped Gen. (ret) Wiranto and Gen. (ret) Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono emerge as strong contenders for the July 5 presidential election."  \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020040512e05c00007\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
