\par\par \b \uc2 Stocks up after nightmare run, rupiah down   \b0\par\par\uc2 Rendi A. WitularJakarta   \par \uc2 546 \uc2 words\par \uc2 19 May 2004\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2004 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 After experiencing sharp losses a day earlier, the Jakarta Stock Market ended slightly higher by 1.15 percent on Tuesday as bargain hunters purchased shares amid gains at other Asian bourses.   \par \par \uc2 The Jakarta Composite Index ended up 7.675 points to 676.152, from a day high of 683.259. Volume was 1.73 billion shares worth Rp 1.17 trillion (US$130 million).   \par \par \uc2 Heavyweight state telecommunications firm PT Telkom led gains in selected blue chips, as it ended higher by Rp 100 to Rp 6,700. Its rival PT Indosat also gained Rp 50 to end at Rp 3,325.   \par \par \uc2 Automotive kingpin PT Astra International rose by Rp 300 to Rp 5,400, while cigarette producer PT Gudang Garam surged by Rp 100 to Rp 12,950.   \par \par \uc2 Stock analyst Arwani Pranadjaya of Mandiri Securities said that gains in regional markets had encouraged local bargain hunters to step into the market following recent losses, which made local stock prices considerably low.   \par \par \uc2 "I may say that it was not a rebound, because the increase was not that significant compared to the huge losses on Monday. It was just bargain hunting and consolidation. The market was still cautious over unfavorable global sentiment," said Arwani.   \par \par \uc2 He explained that jitters over rising inflation at home following the weakening of the rupiah and the rising of oil prices, which may burden local manufacturers, would remain a barrier for the Index to rise in the next couple of weeks.   \par \par \uc2 The prospects of higher \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the U.S. and a slowdown in China's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  as the latter struggles to cool down an overheating \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will put further pressure on the stock market, he said.   \par \par \uc2 The combination of the aforementioned \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  issues coupled with political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  ahead of the July presidential election caused heavy losses in the Index on Monday, as it tumbled by 7.5 percent, the biggest one-day decline in the history of the Index.   \par \par \uc2 Meanwhile in Japan, Tokyo's Nikkei Stock Average of 225 issues surged 206.04 points, or 1.96 percent, to 10,711.09 after the Japanese government said gross domestic product had risen by 1.4 percent in the first quarter of this year, higher than analysts projected. Hong Kong's Hang Seng Index surged 104.74 points, or 0.95 percent, to 11,072.39.   \par \par \uc2 Elsewhere, the rupiah failed to track down gains in the stock market as it ended lower against the U.S. dollar following panic buying by the corporate sector due to jitters caused by political, security and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  at home and the strengthening of the greenback against most regional currencies.   \par \par \uc2 The rupiah closed at Rp 9,070 to the dollar, down from Rp 9,010 on Monday.   \par \par \uc2 Director of Currency Management Group Farial Anwar said many corporations had decided to keep their dollars because they feared that the rupiah's depreciation would last for a long period of time, thus burdening their costs for imported materials and dollar-denominated debts.   \par \par \uc2 "Panic buying by the corporate sector has weakened the rupiah. They seem to dismiss the recent comments by \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  officials that the weakening of the rupiah is temporary, and indeed I agree with them," said Farial.    \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020040519e05j000ma\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal54