\par\par \b \uc2 Indonesia makes steady  \highlight22\uc2 economic \highlight\uc2  recovery   \b0\par\par\uc2 Boediono, Jeju Island, South Korea   \par \uc2 680 \uc2 words\par \uc2 21 May 2004\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 7\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2004 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Among countries in this region, Indonesia has been hit by the 1997 crisis hardest and longest. In the past three years or so, however, the country has been slowly but steadily pulling itself out of the crisis.   \par \par \uc2 The year 2003 represented another step on the road to recovery. Prudent \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  and monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  had contributed a continued deceleration in inflation and \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  while the exchange rate strengthened and stabilized. This pattern continued into the first quarter of 2004.   \par \par \uc2 These strengthening fundamentals generated some acceleration in growth in 2003, which was 4.1 percent compared to 3.7 percent in 2002 and 3.3 percent in 2001.   \par \par \uc2 The sources of growth had been consumption and, more recently, exports, while investment continued to be weak. There are a number of reasons for the poor investment performance, but the most serious may be the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  around the outcome of the election.   \par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  election was concluded successfully in April. Now a very competitive presidential race is getting under way. A first-round election is set for July 5 and the runoff on Sept. 20 if one of the candidates does not receive more than 50 percent of the votes.   \par \par \uc2 Indications so far are giving us confidence that the process will go well and that the improvements to the electoral system will yield a stronger accountable government and parliament.   \par \par \uc2 However, our reform agenda is too pressing to wait for the results of the election. Last year the government issued a White Paper that provides a detailed macroeconomic and structural reform strategy for 2003 and 2004.   \par \par \uc2 Key recent reform accomplishments include the establishment of a National Export and Investment Team chaired by the President and tasked with addressing critical obstacles.   \par \par \uc2 In April a one-roof licensing service was created to speed up investment approvals. With the assistance of the donor community, \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  and customs reform, which was begun last year, continues to progress, and a reorganization of the Ministry of Finance to enhance budgeting and treasury operations is getting under way.   \par \par \uc2 We will shortly submit new \b \highlight22\uc2 tax legislation\b0 \highlight\uc2  to the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  with provisions we believe will spur investment and job creation.   \par \par \uc2 On the critical governance agenda, the Anti-Corruption Committee should be operational shortly and Anti-Money Laundering Agency is now actively investigating cases.   \par \par \uc2 The outlook is positive. An improving global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  should increase exports and investment later this year and 2005. We now expect growth in 2004 to reach close to 5 percent, and inflation will be below 6 percent. This will set the stage for a pick-up in growth and continued stability in 2005.   \par \par \uc2 Next year, we project growth will be 5 to 5.5 percent, inflation in the 5 percent range and short-term \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  around 7 percent.   \par \par \uc2 With our recovery back on track, Indonesia is now at or close to pre-crisis poverty levels. We will use this momentum to not only meet but exceed the Millennium Development Goals and we look to ADB to support our effort.   \par \par \uc2 For our part we intend to implement a Poverty Strategy that provides a comprehensive framework and focus for anti-poverty actions.   \par \par \uc2 We would like to commend ADB in its efforts to develop new financial and developing instruments that can assist governments and private sectors to find a longerterm local currency financing for infrastructure and other projects.   \par \par \uc2 This effort dovetails with our macroeconomic strategy to bring down long-term \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  to spur private investment while building more active and efficient capital markets.   \par \par \uc2 We look forward to working with ADB on this and hope this effort will result in an attractive product for long term local currency financing.   \par \par \uc2 We are very pleased to learn that the Asian Development Fund (ADF) negotiation has come to a successful conclusion. This will enable ADB to enhance its efforts to combat poverty.   \par \par \uc2 The writer is Indonesia's minister of finance. This article was condensed from a speech he delivered at the annual meeting of the Asian Development Bank in South Korea last week.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020040520e05l0000u\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
