.   \par \par \uc2 "Investors are nervous and cautious because of the decline in the rupiah, which may force the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  to increase its benchmark interest rate to help curb inflation. The market is still volatile," said Radianto.   \par \par \uc2 Domestic real interest rate is currently around 2 percent, which is relatively lower than the rates in other countries. This low interest rate environment could help accelerate \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth.   \par \par \uc2 A sharp decline in the rupiah would push prices of imported goods higher, thus creating inflationary pressures. Last month, inflation accelerated to 5.9 percent from 5.1 percent in March.   \par \par \uc2 The rupiah has been under severe pressure during the past month as many investors switched some of their rupiah-based assets to dollar-based assets on expectations that the U.S. Federal Reserve would start raising its 46-year-low interest rate next month.   \par \par \uc2 The rupiah fell to a 19-month low against the U.S. dollar on Tuesday, closing at Rp 9,260 against the dollar.   \par \par \uc2 Indeed, government bond prices in the secondary market have dropped in recent weeks on interest rate and rupiah concerns, with foreign investors largely liquidating their positions.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020040525e05q00002\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
