\par\par \b \uc2 Weak rupiah, political tension send stocks tumbling down  \b0\par\par\uc2 The Jakarta Post , Jakarta  \par \uc2 512 \uc2 words\par \uc2 5 June 2004\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 2\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2004 The Jakarta Post  \par \par \uc2 Jakarta shares plunged on Friday amid lingering worries of the sharp depreciation in the value of the rupiah against the U.S. dollar and rising political tension ahead of next month's presidential election.  \par \par \uc2 The Jakarta Stock Exchange Composite Index fell by 2.9 percent, or 21.105 points at 697.937, which was slightly higher than its intra-day low of 689.536.  \par \par \uc2 Falls led gainers 87 to 14, with 57 stocks unchanged. Volume was at 1.3 billion shares valued at Rp 1.3 trillion (US$137.57 million).  \par \par \uc2 Traders said that foreign investors sold shares heavily after the rupiah tumbled to around Rp 9,540 per dollar at one point during the day. Suspected \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  intervention managed to lift the local unit, and closed at Rp 9,465, little changed from Wednesday's close of Rp 9,470. The local financial market was closed on Thursday for a \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  holiday.  \par \par \uc2 The rupiah has been the worst performing currency in the Asia region, falling by around 11 percent so far this year. A sharp drop in the value of the rupiah would hurt companies as it would be more expensive to import raw materials and costly to repay maturing foreign debts.  \par \par \uc2 Concerns over the domestic political situation, high global crude oil prices and losses in many Asian markets after Wall Street's fall overnight added to the negative sentiment.  \par \par \uc2 "There was heavy selling," said a trader with Paramitra Securities as quoted by Dow Jones .  \par \par \uc2 "Some investors may be thinking it's time to play it safe and switch out of Indonesian assets," Paula Komarudin, who helps manage the equivalent of $1.1 billion in assets at PT Manulife Asset Management, was quoted by Bloomberg. .  \par \par \uc2 Bluechip telecommunications firm PT Telkom and bank shares led the Friday fall in the local stock market, the fourth consecutive drop this week.  \par \par \uc2 Telkom, the country's largest telecom firm and the largest counter in the exchange, dropped by 5.5 percent, or Rp 400 to Rp 6,850 per share. Telkom had a $424.3 million debt in US dollars, more than a third of its total debt.  \par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, Bank Mandiri, the largest bank in the country, plunged 6.3 percent, or Rp 75 to Rp 1,125.  \par \par \uc2 Dealers attributed the selling of banking shares to the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 's plan to increase the \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  requirement for commercial banks to defend the rupiah.  \par \par \uc2 In addition to \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  factors both at home and overseas, the rupiah has been badly affected by rising political tension at home as the month-long campaign for the country's first direct presidential elections began on Tuesday, resulting in worries about possible clashes among political supporters.  \par \par \uc2 Nervous companies continued to buy dollars on fears the local unit would continue to decline amid the political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 .  \par \par \uc2 "Local companies continued amassing dollars as they expect the rupiah to remain under pressure ahead of the July presidential election," a dealer said. "\b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  seems to be the main dollar supplier today."  \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020040604e06500007\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
